---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="A little about Niall Walsh — who I am and what I write about."
>
  <div class="article-page">
    <a href="/" class="back-link" aria-label="Back to all posts">
      <svg
        xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
        width="16"
        height="16"
        viewBox="0 0 24 24"
        fill="none"
        stroke="currentColor"
        stroke-width="2"
        stroke-linecap="round"
        stroke-linejoin="round"
        aria-hidden="true"
      >
        <line x1="19" y1="12" x2="5" y2="12"></line>
        <polyline points="12 19 5 12 12 5"></polyline>
      </svg>
      All posts
    </a>

    <header class="page-header">
      <h1 class="article-title">About</h1>
    </header>

    <div class="article-prose"><div class="prose">
      <p class="about-intro">
        Hi, I'm Niall. I write about ideas, the craft of making things, and the
        places where technology and culture collide.
      </p>

      <p>
        I've been writing online for a few years — first on Medium, now here.
        This site is my own corner of the internet: no algorithm, no engagement
        metrics, just essays and notes at whatever pace feels right.
      </p>

      <p>
        The things I think and write about most: software and how it shapes
        behaviour, the practice of writing itself, design as a way of thinking,
        and whatever I happen to be reading.
      </p>

      <h2>Get in touch</h2>

      <p>
        The best way to reach me is by email:
        <a href="mailto:nbwalsh@gmail.com">nbwalsh@gmail.com</a>.
        I read everything and reply to most things, eventually.
      </p>

      <h2>The site</h2>

      <p>
        Built with <a href="https://astro.build" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Astro</a>,
        written in Markdown, hosted as static HTML. No tracking, no analytics,
        no third-party scripts beyond the fonts.
      </p>

      <p>
        The typefaces are
        <a href="https://fonts.google.com/specimen/Playfair+Display" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Playfair Display</a>
        for display headings,
        <a href="https://fonts.google.com/specimen/Lora" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Lora</a>
        for body text, and
        <a href="https://fonts.google.com/specimen/Inter" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Inter</a>
        for UI elements. The design draws loosely on the editorial aesthetic of the
        <a href="https://harvardfilmarchive.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Harvard Film Archive</a>
        — sparse, typographically bold, content-first.
      </p>

      <p>
        Each post has an accompanying image generated with AI. The visual style is
        inspired by the 1950s–60s film poster work of
        <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saul_Bass" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Saul Bass</a>
        and
        <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Brownjohn" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Robert Brownjohn</a>
        — flat geometry, limited palettes, a single photographic fragment, and a
        strong sense of directional tension. The images are generated from bespoke
        prompts written for each post.
      </p>

      <p>
        There's an <a href="/rss.xml">RSS feed</a> if you'd like to follow along
        without the social media overhead.
      </p>
    </div></div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
